On similar grounds is formed the scholastic distinction of abstract and concrete te1·1ns; since in the former the attribute is considered apart from the subject in which it is perceived by the senses: e. g. sight presents to us only albem the mind forms the conception albedo. And so Universals are gained by abso-action, i. e. by* separating the phenomena in which a given group of individuals resemble each other froin those in which they differ. For this reason Locke calls all universals abso-acc aleas,- a phrase etymologically allowable‚ but liable to be confounded with the scholastic use of the word αὐδῶ-εισι in a different sense.
